HAVING a pay rise is one of the most important things any worker can ask for, writes Lynne Rapley. But is it possible for politicians to be tough enough?

All the evidence tells us that pay restraint is not working. And that there is no quick fix.

We’ve been here before. In the early 1990s there was a sharp rise in the minimum wage. It was clearly having an effect on the jobs market as people struggled to find work.

But a similar rise in the minimum wage also coincided with a sharp fall in unemployment.

Our politicians have been saying the same thing for years: that it is wrong to take money out of the economy without a clear benefit for the economy as a whole. But they have shown no evidence that they think this way.

The reality is that the minimum wage is a blunt instrument. It is too easy to just increase it by a few notches.

The minimum wage is a pay barrier.

Theoretically, the minimum wage could be increased by a large amount without any negative effect on employment. But you can’t actually do this, because if you do you create a great incentive for employers to fire people.

