A:

I'm not sure I understand your question correctly, but one way to achieve this would be to use the vignette option.  I'm not sure what you mean by "output material in this way" but I'm assuming you're talking about the output of each vignette.  If this is the case, you can set the vignette option to point to a file containing the contents of each vignette.  For example, when I run esrip:
> vignette("cups")
> vignette("version-0.1.9.9000")
> vignette("version-0.2.1.9000")

I get a file called "vignettes" containing the two vignettes:
> vignettes
[1] "version-0.1.9.9000"
[2] "version-0.2.1.9000"

You can then use the output option to specify the path of the file containing the vignettes:
> esrip -o vignettes.txt

This should result in two vignette files containing the contents of the two vignettes.  I'm not sure if this is what you're looking for but it's what I was able to figure out after reading the help page on the vignette option.

