[Plasmapheresis in the treatment of primary nephrotic syndrome].
The effectiveness of plasmapheresis in the treatment of primary nephrotic syndrome determined by light microscopy was evaluated in a group of 25 children studied between 1983 and 1987. Eighteen children (72%) responded to treatment. Ten of them had a complete remission, six had a partial remission and one had a relapse. In the remaining four children the development of the disease was stopped but the patient developed renal insufficiency. The minimum number of treatments required for a partial remission was two in six patients, three in four patients, and four in one patient. The remission period was between 1 to 4 months. No significant side effects were observed. It is concluded that plasmapheresis in the treatment of primary nephrotic syndrome is a useful method and that its role should be evaluated in a prospective trial. The cost of this treatment may be reduced by the large number of patients who could benefit from it.Q:

